1️⃣ Arrays & Lists
Key Concepts:
•	Access: arr[i]
•	Length: len(arr)
•	Append: arr.append(x)
•	Remove: arr.remove(x) or [x for x in arr if x!=val]
•	Slicing:
o	arr[::-1] → reverse
o	arr[1:] + arr[:1] → rotate left
o	arr[-1:] + arr[:-1] → rotate right
•	Check sorted: arr == sorted(arr)
Common Operations:
•	Max: max(arr) or loop
•	Min: min(arr) or loop
•	Sum: sum(arr) or loop
•	Count condition: sum(1 for x in arr if x%2==0)
•	Unique: list(set(arr))
•	Intersection/Union: list(set(a) & set(b)), list(set(a) | set(b))
•	Next greater: loop for i,j nested
Tips:
•	Use loops for small datasets (<1000)
•	Use sets for uniqueness/intersection
•	For rotation, slicing is easiest
________________________________________
2️⃣ Strings
Key Concepts:
•	Indexing: s[i]
•	Slicing: s[start:end:step]
•	Length: len(s)
•	Split: s.split() → words
•	Join: " ".join(list_of_words)
Common Operations:
•	Reverse string: s[::-1]
•	Palindrome: s == s[::-1]
•	Count vowels/consonants: for c in s: if c in "aeiou": ...
•	Remove spaces: s.replace(" ","")
•	Capitalize words: " ".join([w.capitalize() for w in s.split()])
•	Substring check: "sub" in s
•	First non-repeating: loop + s.count(c)
Tips:
•	Strings are immutable → need new string for modifications
•	For frequency, use dict
________________________________________
3️⃣ Hashing / Dictionaries
Key Concepts:
•	Create: d = {}
•	Add/update: d[key] = value
•	Access: d.get(key, default)
•	Iterate: for k,v in d.items(): ...
•	Setdefault: d.setdefault(key, []).append(value)
Common Patterns:
•	Frequency counting: for x in arr: d[x] = d.get(x,0)+1
•	Most frequent: max(d, key=d.get)
•	Remove duplicates: track seen set
•	Intersection of keys: set(d1) & set(d2)
•	Merge dicts: d1.update(d2)
Tips:
•	Use set() for unique checks
•	Use dict for counting & grouping
________________________________________
4️⃣ Stack & Queue
Stack:
•	LIFO → push/pop:
stack = []
stack.append(x)
stack.pop()
•	Reverse stack: stack[::-1]
Queue:
•	FIFO → enqueue/dequeue:
queue = []
queue.append(x) # enqueue
queue.pop(0)    # dequeue
Common Patterns:
•	Balanced parentheses: push open, pop if match closing
•	Next greater element: use stack for O(n)
•	Reverse order → stack pop
Tips:
•	Lists can simulate both stack and queue
•	For high performance queue, use collections.deque
________________________________________
5️⃣ Recursion / Loop Logic
Factorial: n! = n * (n-1)!
Fibonacci: F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
Tips:
•	Loops can simulate recursion for small numbers
•	Recursion stack limited in Python → prefer iterative if n large
Common Operations:
•	Reverse string/number: recursion or loop
•	Sum digits: sum(int(d) for d in str(n))
•	Print 1→n or n→1: for i in range(1,n+1) or range(n,0,-1)
________________________________________
6️⃣ Searching
Linear Search: loop through array → O(n)
Binary Search: sorted array → O(log n)
l,r = 0,len(arr)-1
while l <= r:
    mid = (l+r)//2
    if arr[mid]==target: ...
Tips:
•	Always check sorted array for binary search
•	First/last occurrence → adjust l and r
________________________________________
7️⃣ Sorting
Bubble Sort: swap adjacent if wrong order
Selection Sort: select min for each position
Insertion Sort: insert element in correct position
Python Tip: use sorted(arr) for real problems
________________________________________
8️⃣ Math / Number Theory
Prime Check: loop till sqrt(n), check divisibility
GCD: Euclid’s algorithm
while b:
    a,b = b,a%b
LCM: (a*b)//GCD(a,b)
Armstrong Number: sum of digits^power = number
Perfect Number: sum of divisors = number
Power of 2: n > 0 and (n & (n-1))==0
Binary conversion: bin(n)[2:]
________________________________________
9️⃣ Bit Manipulation
•	Count set bits: while n: count += n&1; n >>=1
•	Swap without temp: a = a+b; b=a-b; a=a-b
